<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-bases" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Bases and dimension</title>

 <definition xml:id="def-basis">
<statement>
<p>
A <term>basis</term> for <m>\R^n</m> is a set of vectors 
<m>\mathcal{B}=\{\vect{v}_1,\dots,\vect{v}_k\}\subseteq \R^n</m> such that 
<ul>

  <li>
  <p> 
  <m>\lspan(\mathcal{B})=\R^n</m>, and
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  <m>\mathcal{B}</m> is linearly independent. 
  </p>
  </li>
  
</ul>

</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<remark xml:id="rem-basis-for-gen-vec-space">
<statement>
<p>
Note that the same definition holds in general: a basis for a vector space <m>V</m> 
is a subset of <m>V</m> that spans <m>V</m> and is linearly independent. 
</p>
</statement>
</remark>

<example xml:id="ex-standard-basis-is-basis">
<statement>
<p>
The standard basis <m>\{\vect{e}_1,\dots,\vect{e}_n\}</m> is a basis for <m>\R^n</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-finding-a-basis">
<statement>
<p>
Find a basis for 
<md>
\lspan\left(\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\3\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}-2\\0\\4\end{bmatrix},
\begin{bmatrix}0\\4\\10\end{bmatrix}\right).
</md>
</p>
<p>
We need to check for linear independence. We have
<md>
<mrow>
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}1\amp -2\amp 0\amp 0\\2\amp 0\amp 4\amp 0\\3\amp 4\amp 10\amp 0\end{amatrix}
\amp\xrightarrow[R_3\to R_3-3R_1]{R_2\to R_2-2R_1}
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}1\amp -2\amp 0\amp 0\\0\amp 4\amp 4\amp 0\\0\amp 10\amp 10\amp 0\end{amatrix}\\
\amp\xrightarrow{R_3\to R_3-\frac{10}{4}R_2}
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}1\amp -2\amp 0\amp 0\\0\amp 4\amp 4\amp 0\\0\amp 0\amp 0\amp 0\end{amatrix}
</mrow>
</md>.
Let <m>z=t</m>, <m>t\in\R</m>. Then
<md>
4y+4z=0\implies 4y+4t=0\implies y=-t,
</md>
and
<md>
x-2y=0\implies x+2t=0\implies x=-2t.
</md>
</p>
<p>
Since there are infinite solutions here, we know the vectors are not linearly independent. 
In particular, if we take <m>t=1</m>, then we get solution <m>x=-2,y=-1,z=1</m>, and so
<md>
-2\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\3\end{bmatrix}-\begin{bmatrix}-2\\0\\4\end{bmatrix}
+\begin{bmatrix}0\\4\\10\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}0\\0\\0\end{bmatrix},
</md>
or
<md>
\begin{bmatrix}0\\4\\10\end{bmatrix}=2\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\3\end{bmatrix}
+\begin{bmatrix}-2\\0\\4\end{bmatrix}.
</md>
This means that <m>\begin{bmatrix}0\\4\\10\end{bmatrix}</m> is in the span of the other two vectors,
and hence we have 
<md>
\lspan\left(\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\3\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}-2\\0\\4\end{bmatrix},
\begin{bmatrix}0\\4\\10\end{bmatrix}\right)=\lspan\left(\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\3\end{bmatrix}, 
\begin{bmatrix}-2\\0\\4\end{bmatrix}\right).
</md>
Since <m>\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\3\end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\begin{bmatrix}-2\\0\\4\end{bmatrix}</m>
are linearly independent, they form a basis for the original span.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<remark xml:id="rem-comments-on-span-example">
<statement>
<p>
<ol>

  <li>
  <p> 
  In the above example we threw away the vector <m>\begin{bmatrix}0\\4\\10\end{bmatrix}</m>
  from the span as it was not needed. In that example we could have thrown away any of the
  vectors (why?), but this is not always the case. For example, we have
  <md>
<mrow>
\lspan\left(\begin{bmatrix}-1\\2\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}3\\5\end{bmatrix},
\begin{bmatrix}6\\10\end{bmatrix}\right) \amp = 
\lspan\left(\begin{bmatrix}-1\\2\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}3\\5\end{bmatrix}\right)\\
\amp \not= \lspan\left(\begin{bmatrix}3\\5\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}6\\10\end{bmatrix}\right).
</mrow>
</md>
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  The working in the previous example was fairly detailed. In <xref ref="sec-rank-nullity-theorem"/> 
  we will see 
  a more streamlined (and much easier) way of dealing with such an example.
  </p>
  </li>
  
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
</remark>


<theorem xml:id="thm-basis-theorem">
<title>(Basis Theorem)</title>
<statement>
<p>
Any two bases of a vector space have the same number of elements.
</p>
</statement>
</theorem>

<p>
The proof of the Basis Theorem is within the scope of the unit, but it is very fiddly, so we
will leave it as an exercise (to at least look up and understand if you are keen). But note 
what it means: the number of elements in a basis is a unique number we can associate 
to a vector space. So let's give this number a name!
</p>

<definition xml:id="def-dimension">
<statement>
<p>
The <term>dimension</term> of a vector space <m>V</m>, denoted <m>\operatorname{dim}(V)</m>, 
is the number of elements in a basis for <m>V</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<example xml:id="ex-dim-of-Rn">
<statement>
<p>
So what is the dimension of <m>\R^n</m>? 
</p>
<p>
  Since we know that 
the standard basis <m>\{\vect{e}_1,\dots,\vect{e}_n\}</m> is a basis for <m>\R^n</m>, we have
<m>\operatorname{dim}(\R^n)=n</m>. This matches our expectation: <m>\R^3</m> is 3-dimensional!
</p>
</statement>
</example>

</section>